âœ… Exactly right!
To add each new block to the blockchain, miners must complete the costly Proof of Work process â€” and that means:

ğŸ” Repeatedly changing the nonce
until they find a hash that meets the difficulty target (e.g., starts with a certain number of zeros).

ğŸ’¡ Why Is This Costly Step Necessary?
1. To secure the blockchain ğŸ”
Proof of Work (PoW) makes it very hard to alter past blocks.

If someone wants to change a block, theyâ€™d need to remine all blocks after it, which takes immense computing power.

2. To prevent spam and fraud ğŸš«
It ensures that only those who spend real resources (electricity, computation) can add a block.

This protects the network from being flooded with fake blocks.

3. To maintain decentralization ğŸŒ
Every miner has an equal chance to find the right nonce.

No single central party controls which block gets added.

âš™ï¸ So the process for every new block is:
pgsql
Copy
Edit
1. Collect valid transactions
2. Add metadata (timestamp, previous hash, etc.)
3. Start at nonce = 0
4. Keep changing nonce â†’ Hash the block
5. Check if hash meets difficulty
6. If yes â†’ Add block to blockchain
7. Broadcast it to all other nodes
And this process is repeated for every single new block.

ğŸª™ Bonus: Why Do Miners Do This?
Because the first miner to solve it gets rewarded with:

Newly minted Bitcoin (block reward)

Transaction fees from the block

ğŸ”¥ Final Words
Yes â€” this is why Bitcoin is called "proof-of-work". The "work" is this difficult search for the correct nonce.
Itâ€™s computationally expensive, but thatâ€™s what makes it secure, trustless, and tamper-resistant.

